The high-resolution TEM (HRTEM) images of CDs and Pd/CDs are shown in Fig. 4
                        . It can be seen that there are apparent lattice fringes with the plane spacings of 0.21 nm in CDs, closing to spacing of (110) lattice of graphitic carbon (Fig. 4a). For Pd/CDs, HRTEM image shows that Pd NPs were embedded in CDs with the crystal plane spacings of 0.23 nm and 0.20 nm assigned to Pd (111) and Pd (200) [29], respectively (Fig. 4b). CDs (110) and Pd (220) nanoparticles are closely combined, which fully indicates the successful synthesis of Pd/CDs nanocatalyst. Bright spots in selected area diffraction (SAED) pattern of CDs and Pd/CDs (Fig. 4c & d) confirm the crystalline phase of the synthesized nanocatalyst. The rings with different d-spacings of 0.22 nm and 0.23 nm are indexed with the face-centered cubic unit cell dimensions of CDs (110) and Pd (111) nanoparticles (JCPDS file no.87-0638), respectively. It is also confirmed with the previous XRD characterization results. The presence of Pd in the Pd/CDs catalyst is also confirmed by the EDS and energy-dispersive X-ray (EDX) analysis (Fig. 5
                        ).

The textural features of CDs and Pd/CDs were investigated by BET analysis as shown in Table 2
                        . It is found that they have relatively low specific surface area of 16.0 and 9.7 m2·g−1, respectively. With the introduction of Pd particles, the pore volume and the average pore diameter of Pd/CDs both decrease slightly, which indicates that Pd occupies part of the pore of CDs. Moreover, the N2 adsorption-desorption of CDs and Pd/CDs both exhibit type IV isotherms (Fig. 8
                        ). There is also an obvious Type H4 hysteresis loop, indicating that the material has the characteristics of typical mesoporous materials [34]

The recyclability of Pd/CDs under the optimal reaction conditions was performed to explore the stability of catalyst. As shown in Fig. 16
                        , after four cycles, vanillin conversion was still as high as 97.8 %, while the selectivity of MMP decreased to 87.1 %. The reason may be that part of Pd leached from the surface of CDs under vigorous stirring and high temperature during the reaction (Table 4
                        ), resulting in the loss of active metal and reduced catalytic activity. The leaching rate of Pd metal gradually increased with the number of cycles. However, the catalyst eventually became stable after three cycles.
